INTRODUCTION

Head and neck squamous cell carcinoma (HNSCC) is the 8th leading cancer worldwide with almost 650,000 new cases diagnosed every year and 350,000 cancer-related deaths annually [-].
('Head cell carcinoma', 'is', 'cancer')

Although advancements in the anti-cancer treatments including surgery, radiation and chemotherapy have increased the local control of HNSCC, the overall survival rates have not improved significantly over the last three decades [, ].
('advancements in treatments including surgery', 'have increased', 'control of HNSCC')

Five year survival rates for patients with early stage localized head and neck cancers are more that 80% but drop to 40% when the disease has spread to the neck nodes, and to below 20% for patients with distant metastatic disease [].
('disease', 'has spread to', 'neck nodes')

Cisplatin is one of the most widely used chemotherapeutic agent for the treatment of head and neck cancers [].

However, despite an initial favorable response, many patients acquire resistance to it leading to treatment failures [].
('patients', 'acquire', 'resistance to it leading to treatment failures')

Therefore, it is important to understand the molecular mechanisms that contribute to drug resistance in order to identify novel therapeutic targets for head and neck cancer.

Recent studies have highlighted the role of histone deacetylases (HDACs) in regulating a number of genes that are involved in both cancer initiation and cancer progression [-].
('studies', 'have highlighted', 'role of histone deacetylases')

Chromatin configuration is tightly regulated by histone acetylation and deacetylation process and this balance between histone acetylation and deacetylation determines the level at which a particular gene is transcribed [].
('balance between histone acetylation', 'determines', 'level')
('Chromatin configuration', 'is regulated by', 'histone acetylation')
('Chromatin configuration', 'determines', 'level')

Histone acetylation by histone acetyltransferase (HAT) relaxes the chromatin, thereby allowing transcription factors and RNA polymerase II recruitment.
('Histone acetylation by histone acetyltransferase', 'relaxes', 'chromatin')

HDACs remove the acetyl groups from histones, creating a non-permissive chromatin that represses gene transcription [].
('HDACs', 'remove', 'acetyl groups')

Importantly, most of the genes repressed by HDACs are tumor suppressors, cell cycle regulators or apoptosis inducers [].

HDACs also bind and deacetylate a number of other proteins including transcription factors [].
('HDACs', 'deacetylate', 'number of proteins including transcription factors')

Recent studies have shown that HDACs can regulate the self-renewal of cancer stem cells by modulating nanog expression [, ].
('HDACs', 'can regulate', 'the')

In humans, 18 HDACs have been identified and grouped in four classes; class I comprises of HDAC1-3 and 8; class II comprises HDACs 4-7, 9 and 10; class III comprises the NAD+-dependent HDACs (SIRT1-7) and class IV comprises HDAC11, which has some features of both class I and Class II HDACs [, ].
('class', 'comprises', 'HDACs')
('NAD', 'comprises', 'HDAC11')
('class', 'comprises', 'HDAC11')
('HDACs', 'grouped in', 'classes')

Several inhibitors of HDACs have been developed in the last decade and many HDAC inhibitors are in clinical trials for the treatment of solid and hematological malignancies [-].
('HDAC inhibitors', 'are in', 'trials')
('inhibitors of HDACs', 'have been developed in', 'decade')
('inhibitors of HDACs', 'are in', 'trials')

Vorinostat (Suberoyanilide hydroxamic acid, SAHA) is one of the most advanced pan-HDAC inhibitor that was approved by FDA in 2006 for the treatment of cutaneous T-cell lymphoma [].

SAHA was initially developed as a derivative of hexamethylene bisacetamide (HMBA) to treat myelodysplatic syndrome and acute myelodysplastic leukemia [].
('SAHA', 'was developed as', 'derivative of hexamethylene bisacetamide to treat syndrome leukemia')

Recent studies have shown that SAHA has significant anti-cancer activities against many solid tumors [, ].
('SAHA', 'has', 'activities against tumors')

SAHA has been shown to inhibit all 11 known human class I and II HDACs [].
('SAHA', 'has been shown to inhibit', 'class HDACs')

In addition to inhibiting the activity of HDACs, SAHA is also known to regulate the expression of a number of other proteins including transcription factors, pro-apoptotic proteins and anti-apoptotic proteins [].
('SAHA', 'is known to regulate', 'expression of number of proteins including transcription factors')

In this report, we demonstrate that the expression of HDAC1, 2 and 6 is significantly upregulated in head and neck cancer cells.
('expression of HDAC1', 'is upregulated in', 'head cancer cells')

In addition, HDACs expression is further increased in cisplatin resistant (CisR) cells.
('HDACs expression', 'is increased in', 'cisplatin cells')

HDAC1 and 2 knockdown in cisplatin-resistant cell lines by siRNA significantly reversed cisplatin resistance and tumorsphere formation.

Similarly, treatment with pan-HDAC inhibitor SAHA significantly enhanced the anti-tumor effects of cisplatin in a synergistic manner.
('treatment with inhibitor SAHA', 'enhanced', 'effects of cisplatin')

In addition, SAHA treatment significantly decreased tumorsphere formation and markedly reduced nanog and survivin expression.
('SAHA treatment', 'decreased', 'tumorsphere formation')
('SAHA treatment', 'reduced', 'nanog expression')

Similar to the in vitro results, SAHA and cisplatin combination treatment significantly decreased tumor growth and tumor metastasis, in vivo.
('SAHA combination treatment', 'decreased', 'tumor growth tumor metastasis')

